Cell["\<\
Hence, the odds ratio is equal to OR=(2x4)/(3x1)=8/3=2.66. Hence, it means \
that the chance of rating a coffee as bad is 2.66 higher for the journalist X \
compared to journalist Y.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.947119337360776*^9, 3.947119363597443*^9}, {
  3.947119407111167*^9, 
  3.947119439940364*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"53861a06-9438-4390-b077-\
31a18bc99698"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
2. We are interested in the pizza delivery data previously discussed.
(a) Read in the data and create two new binary variables which describe whether
a pizza was hot (>65 \[EmptySmallCircle]C) and the delivery time was short \
(<30 min). Create a
contingency table for the two new variables.
(b) Calculate and interpret the odds ratio for the contingency table from \
(a).
(c) Use Cramer\[CloseCurlyQuote]s V and a stacked bar chart to explore the \
association between the categorical time and temperature variables.
(d) Draw a scatter plot for the continuous time and temperature variables. \
Determine
both the Bravais\[Dash]Pearson and Spearman correlation coefficients.
(e) Use methods of your choice to explore the relationship between \
temperature
and driver, operator, number of ordered pizzas and bill. Is it clear which of \
the
variables influence the pizza temperature?\
\>", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9471200295656347`*^9, 3.9471200303704433`*^9}, {
  3.947120063241949*^9, 
  3.94712011070362*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7ebc109c-867f-498b-96af-\
8e02dd71cc25"],

